11
00:00:47,778 --> 00:00:50,005
LISA:
<i>Our Lord, Buddha, says,</i>

12
00:00:50,018 --> 00:00:53,396
<i>"The secret of existence
is to pass beyond fear."</i>

13
00:00:53,417 --> 00:00:55,952
<i>My brother is about
to meet fear...</i>

14
00:00:55,972 --> 00:00:59,003
<i>and as usual...
he won't pass.</i>

15
00:01:02,144 --> 00:01:04,204
Wake up, Lis! It's the
last day of school!

16
00:01:04,217 --> 00:01:05,484
(groans)

17
00:01:05,509 --> 00:01:07,980
Wake up, Maggs!
It's the last day of school!

18
00:01:07,986 --> 00:01:09,471
(singsongy):
Last day of school!

19
00:01:09,500 --> 00:01:10,967
(metal clanging rhythmically)
Last day of school!

20
00:01:10,987 --> 00:01:14,139
Found my summer hobby!
Banging pots together!

21
00:01:14,159 --> 00:01:15,979
Don't worry, Marge.
As a favor to you,

22
00:01:16,012 --> 00:01:21,009
I'm enrolling that precious little
jerk in this fresh air summer camp.

23
00:01:22,206 --> 00:01:24,366
That's a prison road crew.

24
00:01:24,392 --> 00:01:26,865
I did that last summer.
I'm not allowed back.

25
00:01:26,884 --> 00:01:28,685
(humming)

26
00:01:28,719 --> 00:01:29,577
(whirring)

27
00:01:29,597 --> 00:01:32,373
Good-bye forever,
multiplication!

28
00:01:33,656 --> 00:01:34,905
(slurps)

29
00:01:34,931 --> 00:01:37,361
Uh... needs more
numerators.

30
00:01:39,049 --> 00:01:41,622
Ah, "July 4th..."
What the...?

31
00:01:41,649 --> 00:01:43,162
No fireworks?!

32
00:01:43,175 --> 00:01:46,840
Can't this stupid city entertain
me one night a year?!

33
00:01:46,863 --> 00:01:48,183
The city's broke.

34
00:01:48,198 --> 00:01:51,868
The fire department has to raise
money by delivering pizza.

35
00:01:54,483 --> 00:01:56,530
My baby!

36
00:01:56,540 --> 00:01:58,067
Back ribs!

37
00:01:58,261 --> 00:02:01,768
Marge, when you're broke, that's
when you got to keep up appearances.

38
00:02:01,786 --> 00:02:04,689
The Fourth of July is the one day
a year when our city puts on

39
00:02:04,708 --> 00:02:09,089
her high heels and tube top and
leans into America's car window.

40
00:02:09,438 --> 00:02:11,745
(crying):
God bless her.

41
00:02:13,622 --> 00:02:15,865
LISA: <i>The last day of school.
Field Day.</i>

42
00:02:15,899 --> 00:02:18,207
<i>When you learn to balance</i>
<i>an egg on a spoon</i>

43
00:02:18,220 --> 00:02:21,705
<i>and run with your leg tied to someone
who wouldn't talk to you all year.</i>

44
00:02:21,725 --> 00:02:25,031
Hey! Are you coming to the
after-school pool party?

45
00:02:25,055 --> 00:02:26,857
Not now.

46
00:02:27,964 --> 00:02:30,331
(giggles)

47
00:02:30,351 --> 00:02:32,077
Aw... no fair!

48
00:02:32,108 --> 00:02:34,267
He actually has
three legs.

49
00:02:34,293 --> 00:02:38,224
You lay off my son Tripod!
He won fair and square,

50
00:02:38,248 --> 00:02:42,050
just like my twins
Wheel and Barrow.

51
00:02:42,266 --> 00:02:44,739
Now, take you brother
to the face painting.

52
00:02:44,761 --> 00:02:47,697
But don't make yourselves
up to look all freaky.

53
00:02:48,057 --> 00:02:50,759
One, two, three, toss.

54
00:02:50,787 --> 00:02:52,875
(laughs)

55
00:02:52,915 --> 00:02:57,067
The eggs are supposed to be tossed
between students, not <i>at</i> the principal.

56
00:02:57,087 --> 00:02:59,688
Once more and hurl! Aah!

57
00:02:59,702 --> 00:03:03,231
We will do this until
we get it right.

58
00:03:03,251 --> 00:03:07,014
Look, do you want this to be
your last school memory?

59
00:03:07,041 --> 00:03:08,101
(groans)

60
00:03:09,054 --> 00:03:11,754
Pull harder! What is
wrong with you people?!

61
00:03:12,283 --> 00:03:14,835
Hey. I have thumbs, too.

62
00:03:15,988 --> 00:03:18,204
(chiming)

63
00:03:19,425 --> 00:03:21,393
(yells)

64
00:03:23,256 --> 00:03:26,368
I like the Play-Doh
that comes out the back.

65
00:03:27,001 --> 00:03:29,982
See you next June, Macaroni.

66
00:03:30,009 --> 00:03:31,890
(door latch slides shut)

67
00:03:36,943 --> 00:03:40,948
And now the climactic
Race around the School.

68
00:03:40,967 --> 00:03:45,027
Previous winners include Sideshow
Mel, Señora Bumblebee Man

69
00:03:45,039 --> 00:03:47,779
and Olympian Edwin Moses.

70
00:03:47,794 --> 00:03:50,547
I'll bet your biggest hurdle was
leaving your beloved hometown.

71
00:03:50,567 --> 00:03:54,300
All hurdles are the same size.
Man... who is this loser?

72
00:03:54,327 --> 00:03:56,401
I've got a secret, Bart.

73
00:03:56,414 --> 00:03:58,853
- That's good.
- Want to know what it is?

74
00:03:58,865 --> 00:03:59,892
No.

75
00:03:59,899 --> 00:04:04,412
My secret is I've been training for
this race and no one suspects.

76
00:04:04,418 --> 00:04:05,525
Check it out:

77
00:04:05,545 --> 00:04:07,500
I'm wearing a dummy tummy.

78
00:04:09,202 --> 00:04:12,476
I'm gonna win
and it'll change my life!

79
00:04:15,188 --> 00:04:16,095
Wow!

80
00:04:16,114 --> 00:04:18,521
Breaking that tape
cured your asthma.

81
00:04:18,545 --> 00:04:20,804
(deep voice): Marvelous!
Ha-ha-ha!

82
00:04:20,826 --> 00:04:23,019
(guffaws)

83
00:04:23,536 --> 00:04:24,923
(gasps)

84
00:04:28,081 --> 00:04:30,281
(lisping):
Six on Bart Simpson.

85
00:04:30,294 --> 00:04:32,321
BOTH:
Two on us to win.

86
00:04:32,326 --> 00:04:33,893
$20 on Milhouse.

87
00:04:33,913 --> 00:04:35,566
Milhouse?!
(scoffs)

88
00:04:35,588 --> 00:04:37,708
That's a
thousand-to-one odds.

89
00:04:37,724 --> 00:04:40,004
Perhaps I should take
my action to Willie.

90
00:04:40,017 --> 00:04:41,910
(grunts)
I ain't makin' book no more.

91
00:04:41,961 --> 00:04:43,621
I lost the deed
to my shack!

92
00:04:43,643 --> 00:04:45,750
You are late with
the rent, Willie.

93
00:04:45,770 --> 00:04:48,910
I'll have it by Friday, Mr. U.
I swear.

94
00:04:48,917 --> 00:04:50,277
We can handle your action.

95
00:04:50,303 --> 00:04:52,071
(trumpet playing
in the distance)

96
00:04:52,711 --> 00:04:54,482
Betting is now closed.

97
00:04:56,856 --> 00:04:58,129
(panting)

98
00:04:58,142 --> 00:05:02,784
And now, the 79th running
of the Race around the School.

99
00:05:03,350 --> 00:05:05,803
- Gun in the school!
- What the...?

100
00:05:06,485 --> 00:05:09,218
Just, just go.
And they're off!

101
00:05:09,231 --> 00:05:10,994
<i>We've got a pack of
fifth-graders on the rail,</i>

102
00:05:11,014 --> 00:05:13,436
<i>Simp-son holding
down the center</i>

103
00:05:13,449 --> 00:05:16,868
<i>while Database and Cosine are
still testing the wind speed.</i>

104
00:05:16,877 --> 00:05:19,941
<i>As the runners go into the first
turn, Lewis is in the lead!</i>

105
00:05:19,961 --> 00:05:22,701
<i>Followed by Lovejoy's
daughter, Fat Tony's nephew,</i>

106
00:05:22,708 --> 00:05:23,977
- <i>Brockman's little girl...</i>
- (screams)

107
00:05:23,997 --> 00:05:25,570
<i>...and Jailbird's kid!</i>

108
00:05:25,591 --> 00:05:28,624
<i>The Frank Sinatra kid...
well, he's doing it his way!</i>

109
00:05:28,641 --> 00:05:32,433
Rounding out the pack are all
the kids that we never see.

110
00:05:32,451 --> 00:05:35,338
What's this? Milhouse
takes the lead?

111
00:05:35,361 --> 00:05:38,611
<i>The same boy who sprained his shoulder
doing the Pledge of Allegiance?</i>

112
00:05:38,638 --> 00:05:40,118
(panting)

113
00:05:40,160 --> 00:05:43,473
Uh-oh! If Milhouse wins this
race, we're out a fortune.

114
00:05:43,497 --> 00:05:47,150
Don't worry. The race takes a turn
through the trees where no one can see.

115
00:05:47,172 --> 00:05:49,525
When Milhouse gets there,
you know what to do.

116
00:05:49,545 --> 00:05:53,525
Oh, yeah. Totally.
I mean, it's so obvious.

117
00:05:53,553 --> 00:05:56,020
- Just punch him!
- Exactly.

118
00:05:56,026 --> 00:05:59,980
Right in the nnn...
fff... dee...?

119
00:05:59,986 --> 00:06:01,920
There is no wrong answer!

120
00:06:01,935 --> 00:06:06,128
CHALMERS: <i>And Milhouse, the boy
nobody loves, is widening his lead!</i>

121
00:06:06,161 --> 00:06:07,614
And what does he
have to jump over?

122
00:06:07,640 --> 00:06:10,458
Nothing, that's what.
I'm out of here.

123
00:06:10,490 --> 00:06:12,958
(grunting)

124
00:06:13,072 --> 00:06:15,073
Good job, Edwin.

125
00:06:16,336 --> 00:06:18,343
I'm doing it! I'm doing it!

126
00:06:18,357 --> 00:06:20,490
And when I win, I'm
changing my name.

127
00:06:20,503 --> 00:06:23,588
To something cool
like Winnie!

128
00:06:26,492 --> 00:06:29,561
Did you come to give
me a cup of water?

129
00:06:30,536 --> 00:06:32,048
(both grunt)

130
00:06:32,850 --> 00:06:37,368
The best day of my life just turned
into every other day of my life.

131
00:06:40,026 --> 00:06:42,073
LISA:
<i>Bart faced a terrible choice...</i>

132
00:06:42,095 --> 00:06:46,165
<i>take a beating with his friend
or slither off like a coward.</i>

133
00:06:46,192 --> 00:06:48,611
<i>And like he did with every
multiple choice question</i>

134
00:06:48,630 --> 00:06:52,394
<i>he ever saw,
Bart chose "B."</i>

135
00:06:59,651 --> 00:07:00,964
(crowd cheering)

136
00:07:00,983 --> 00:07:03,219
The winner is Bart Simpson!

137
00:07:03,236 --> 00:07:04,842
LISA:
<i>Bart won a blue ribbon.</i>

138
00:07:04,855 --> 00:07:06,229
<i>But was it worth it?</i>

139
00:07:06,248 --> 00:07:08,289
MARGE:
<i>Lisa! Bath time!</i>

140
00:07:08,307 --> 00:07:10,400
LISA:
<i>Mom! I'm narrating!</i>

141
00:07:10,430 --> 00:07:12,270
MARGE:
<i>The water's gonna get cold!</i>

142
00:07:12,285 --> 00:07:13,819
LISA:
<i>Fine.</i>

143
00:07:17,551 --> 00:07:20,668
LISA: <i>As the pin on the back</i>
<i>of the blue ribbon made its way</i>

144
00:07:20,681 --> 00:07:23,207
<i>through Bart's shirt</i>
<i>and into its housing,</i>

145
00:07:23,227 --> 00:07:27,082
<i>the seeds of his comeuppance
flew out of the woods.</i>

146
00:07:27,106 --> 00:07:31,386
Son! What happened to you in the
dark place behind the school?

147
00:07:31,403 --> 00:07:32,689
Something good?

148
00:07:34,145 --> 00:07:36,858
I'm afraid I
don't remember.

149
00:07:36,875 --> 00:07:38,095
Whew.

150
00:07:38,116 --> 00:07:40,496
Well, it looks like Milhouse
has traumatic amnesia.

151
00:07:40,508 --> 00:07:42,245
He may never remember
what happened to him.

152
00:07:42,261 --> 00:07:45,964
The most important thing is, the
race results are now official.

153
00:07:45,998 --> 00:07:49,536
Now I've got to look at some severe
cases of ice cream headache.

154
00:07:50,389 --> 00:07:52,357
(theme from <i>MASH</i> playing)

155
00:08:03,702 --> 00:08:05,970
(Bart groaning)

156
00:08:08,901 --> 00:08:10,268
(gasps)

157
00:08:10,288 --> 00:08:12,275
Help me, Bart!

158
00:08:13,699 --> 00:08:15,066
(screams)

159
00:08:15,094 --> 00:08:17,034
Help me, Bart!

160
00:08:17,055 --> 00:08:18,530
(shouts)

161
00:08:18,677 --> 00:08:19,444
(gasps)

162
00:08:19,464 --> 00:08:21,893
Help me, Bart!

163
00:08:23,836 --> 00:08:24,936
(gasping)

164
00:08:25,064 --> 00:08:27,997
Why am I having nightmares?
I'm no coward.

165
00:08:28,020 --> 00:08:29,127
(screams)

166
00:08:29,174 --> 00:08:31,750
A chicken feather? Why
would you hand this to me?

167
00:08:31,784 --> 00:08:35,371
Oh, you must've figured out
I chickened out during the race.

168
00:08:35,393 --> 00:08:38,223
Well, who are you
to judge me?

169
00:08:38,763 --> 00:08:40,831
I suck? You suck!

170
00:08:40,852 --> 00:08:43,359
LISA: <i>While Bart was being
outwitted by a baby,</i>

171
00:08:43,382 --> 00:08:47,455
<i>something was coming to a
boil in our pop's brainpan.</i>

172
00:08:47,799 --> 00:08:52,329
Marge, if this stupid, one-reactor town
won't put on a fireworks show, I will.

173
00:08:52,350 --> 00:08:53,997
I've mapped it out.

174
00:08:54,017 --> 00:08:55,155
(laughs)

175
00:08:55,193 --> 00:08:57,305
- Hmm?
- (groans)

176
00:08:58,229 --> 00:09:01,980
Maybe we should just light
sparklers in the backyard.

177
00:09:01,993 --> 00:09:05,075
Eh, I've had my problems
with sparklers.

178
00:09:05,090 --> 00:09:07,231
Fun! Fun! Fun! Fun! Fun!
Fun! Fun! Fun!

179
00:09:07,471 --> 00:09:08,905
(screams)

180
00:09:08,934 --> 00:09:11,834
LISA: <i>But Fourth of July fireworks
were a different story.</i>

181
00:09:11,847 --> 00:09:15,588
<i>They meant more to my dad
than my Mom could ever know.</i>

182
00:09:15,601 --> 00:09:17,468
<i>It was the one night
of every year</i>

183
00:09:17,488 --> 00:09:19,915
<i>that he couldn't hear
his parents argue.</i>

184
00:09:19,941 --> 00:09:24,596
<i>He figured it was because they loved
the fireworks just as much as he did.</i>

185
00:09:25,089 --> 00:09:26,549
I want to take a class!

186
00:09:26,572 --> 00:09:29,973
Why can't you be happy
ironing my shirts?!

187
00:09:30,002 --> 00:09:31,389
I need space!

188
00:09:31,410 --> 00:09:34,209
Then close your eyes
and go to Hawaii!

189
00:09:35,246 --> 00:09:38,284
LISA: <i>With his mom gone,
Homer needed a hero,</i>

190
00:09:38,304 --> 00:09:41,442
<i>and no one was a bigger hero
than the magical little man</i>

191
00:09:41,462 --> 00:09:43,299
<i>behind the controls.</i>

192
00:09:43,336 --> 00:09:45,318
(fireworks whistling)

193
00:09:45,331 --> 00:09:48,774
- Are you God?
- No, no.

194
00:09:48,794 --> 00:09:52,340
But I shoot rockets
into his a-face.

195
00:09:52,364 --> 00:09:57,011
Here's-a my card. Don't
forget to treasure it.

196
00:09:58,015 --> 00:09:59,602
Hmm.

197
00:09:59,608 --> 00:10:02,169
Now let's see. Which
pants have that card?

198
00:10:02,182 --> 00:10:04,395
Board shorts,
interested shorts.

199
00:10:04,416 --> 00:10:06,025
Here we are.

200
00:10:06,812 --> 00:10:08,520
Kaboom.

201
00:10:10,202 --> 00:10:13,255
Giuseppe, I want you to
come out of retirement

202
00:10:13,268 --> 00:10:16,091
for the greatest fireworks
show of your career.

203
00:10:16,104 --> 00:10:19,456
Why do you come here and
remind me of a time in my life

204
00:10:19,469 --> 00:10:22,990
when I made a-tons of money
doing a-what I love?

205
00:10:23,003 --> 00:10:25,556
If the <i>Expendables</i> movies
have taught us anything,

206
00:10:25,569 --> 00:10:29,968
it's that people do their best work
after they're old and forgotten.

207
00:10:29,974 --> 00:10:33,820
Well, I am younger
than Sylvester Stallone.

208
00:10:33,838 --> 00:10:35,518
I will do it!

209
00:10:40,451 --> 00:10:43,555
- Hey, buddy.
- Bart, my truest friend.

210
00:10:43,582 --> 00:10:45,384
I brought you a cake.

211
00:10:45,397 --> 00:10:46,651
Read it.

212
00:10:46,671 --> 00:10:48,663
That's an odd message.

213
00:10:48,680 --> 00:10:51,280
But who am I to
argue with icing?

214
00:10:51,295 --> 00:10:54,295
Will you watch <i>Cassidy
the Crocodile</i> with me?

215
00:10:54,314 --> 00:10:59,046
- Um, that's kind of a baby show.
- It's all I can handle now.

216
00:10:59,076 --> 00:11:00,407
(sighs)

217
00:11:01,600 --> 00:11:05,000
Henrietta Kitten?
Will you marry me?

218
00:11:05,023 --> 00:11:06,763
Meow, meow, maybe.

219
00:11:06,798 --> 00:11:09,628
Why would a kitten marry a crocodile?
Wouldn't it eat her?

220
00:11:09,648 --> 00:11:10,748
(shushes)

221
00:11:10,769 --> 00:11:13,349
Suspension of disbelief.

222
00:11:13,371 --> 00:11:16,158
Friends help friends
in trouble.

223
00:11:16,182 --> 00:11:18,861
No! Turn it off! It's
too intense for me!

224
00:11:18,884 --> 00:11:22,632
Some guys just can't
handle crocodiles.

225
00:11:22,658 --> 00:11:23,828
Is it over yet?

226
00:11:23,862 --> 00:11:25,162
(chicken clucks)

227
00:11:25,184 --> 00:11:28,002
And if you're dissatisfied
for any reason,

228
00:11:28,015 --> 00:11:31,824
I will refund your money
in the form of acorns.

229
00:11:34,372 --> 00:11:35,639
(groans)

230
00:11:35,661 --> 00:11:39,653
Hey, this gunpowder,
it has a-crystal meth in it.

231
00:11:39,678 --> 00:11:44,211
Crystal meth? Then what the heck did
I sell to them Colombian drug lords?

232
00:11:45,897 --> 00:11:49,966
Brandine! We're feuding
with the Escobars again!

233
00:11:49,995 --> 00:11:52,663
Does that mean I ain't
talking to Maria?

234
00:11:52,683 --> 00:11:54,404
Duh! Yes.

235
00:11:54,419 --> 00:11:58,021
Homer, we will get the
fireworks someplace else.

236
00:11:58,477 --> 00:12:01,861
The pig's been eating
the C-4 blocks again!

237
00:12:01,894 --> 00:12:04,028
(burps)

238
00:12:04,616 --> 00:12:06,221
(dog barks)

